export const batch139 = {
  'food.json': {
    base: { id: 'food', title: 'Food', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781650437950 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Common foods are not always good for you',
        text: 'Nutrition experts have not yet agreed on what makes food truly healthy. They know that the human body needs the right foods in the right amounts. But they often disagree about which foods belong in a good diet. The list below covers a few foods that spark the most debate in modern eating.\n\nMeat is the first item. Eating too much meat can be bad for the body. It is linked to long-term sicknesses like cancer and type 2 diabetes, and it can clog the arteries. At the same time, meat has been part of human meals for hundreds of years.\n\nThe main reason meat matters is protein. The body needs protein to stay strong, and an average adult needs about 60 grams each day. Plant foods and eggs only carry small amounts of protein, so meat is the simplest way to meet that need. It is also very helpful for women who deal with low iron from their monthly cycle.\n\nMeat is also rich in vitamins and minerals beyond its protein content. Poultry and eggs are next. Federal food guidelines pushed people away from saturated fats, which made poultry very popular. To keep up, today\'s chickens are raised indoors and fed pellets that speed up growth. Yet eggs from chickens that eat a more natural diet have a much richer mix of nutrients.\n\nMilk and dairy raise their own concerns. Low-fat milk can be just as harmful as whole milk, since studies show it can lead to childhood obesity. Some vegetables actually have more calcium than milk. Milk may not build strong bones and can even lead to weaker bones over time. Still, natural butter from grass-fed cows can be a better choice than many vegetable oils, as long as it stays free of unwanted additives. Plain yogurt with no added sugar is also a fair choice. The lesson is to draw on many food sources and to check the quality of what you buy. Ask where your food came from, whether it was made in bulk, and what is printed on the label.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Meat, eggs, and milk are not the enemy',
        text: 'Nutrition experts have not reached a final verdict on the healthiest diet. They agree the body needs the right foods in the right amounts. Yet they often disagree about which foods truly belong on the plate. The list below covers a few foods that often spark debate in modern eating.\n\nMeat leads the list. Eating too much meat can harm the body. It is tied to long-term problems like cancer and type 2 diabetes, and it can block the arteries. Even so, meat has been a central part of human meals for hundreds of years.\n\nThe main reason meat matters is protein. An average adult needs about 60 grams of protein a day, and plant foods and eggs only carry small amounts. That is why meat is the simplest way to cover daily needs. It is also very helpful for women who lose iron during their monthly cycle.\n\nMeat is also packed with vitamins and minerals beyond its protein. Poultry and eggs come next. Federal food rules warned against saturated fats, which made poultry very popular. To keep up, today\'s chickens are raised indoors and fed pellets that boost growth. Yet eggs from chickens that eat a more natural diet have a richer mix of nutrients.\n\nMilk and dairy raise their own concerns. Low-fat milk can be just as harmful as whole milk, since research links it to childhood obesity. Some vegetables actually have more calcium than milk. Milk may not build strong bones and can even lead to weaker ones over time. Still, natural butter from grass-fed cows can be a better choice than many vegetable oils, as long as it stays free of unwanted additives. Plain yogurt with no added sugar is also a fair choice. The takeaway is to draw on many food sources and to check the quality of what you buy. Ask where the food came from, whether it was made in bulk, and what is printed on the label.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Vegetables alone cannot replace every food group',
        text: 'The first rule of a good diet is to eat food as close to its natural form as possible. Fish, seafood, vegetables, and fruits all play a role, but the quality of each one matters a great deal.\n\nFish and seafood stand out. The human brain is more than half fat, and it needs omega-3 fats to work well. A balanced diet includes both light and dark fish. Dark fish has more omega-3, while both kinds can carry mercury. Eating salmon, tuna, herring, trout, or mackerel about twice a week can support the heart and lower the risk of cancer and depression.\n\nSushi is a healthy choice only when the fish is kept apart from the white rice. Natural fish offers a lot, but it also carries some risk. Farm fish are often fed antibiotics to fight disease from crowded pens. Wild fish can soak up pollution from oil and coal companies. In both cases, traces of those chemicals end up on your plate.\n\nVegetables are the next piece. If you have high blood sugar, lean toward potatoes and away from bread. The best vegetables, like edible flowers, seaweed, and Romanesco broccoli, are organic or wild. Vegetables are the most valuable source of good carbs and should fill a large share of the plate.\n\nEven so, vegetables cannot do the job alone. Take carrots as a case. Many people think carrots are a top source of vitamin A. They are not. Carrots carry beta-carotene, which the body has to convert into vitamin A. Beef liver actually has far more vitamin A than carrots. The same kind of mix-up happens with vitamin C, where meat can offer more than lemons or oranges.\n\nFruit rounds out the picture. Health guides often suggest five to nine servings of fruit and vegetables a day. Vegetables are a safe choice, but fruit can carry a lot of natural sugar. You do not need to cut fruit out, but some fruits, eaten in large amounts, can push up body weight and blood sugar.\n\nAn apple a day still holds up, but raspberries, blackberries, and blueberries carry even more helpful plant nutrients. If you do not grow your own fruit, frozen fruit is a good option. It is usually picked at peak ripeness and keeps most of its nutrients through the freezing process.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Clearing up myths: fats are not all bad, and beans are not all safe',
        text: 'Few topics in nutrition spark more arguments than fat. Some experts blame oils for the obesity crisis, while others suggest a Keto diet that leans on fat to fight fat. It is worth sorting through the noise.\n\nFats and oils sit at the center of the debate. The common claim is that eating fat makes you fat and causes heart disease. The reasoning seems simple. A gram of fat has nine calories, while a gram of carbs has four. So fat should add more weight. A study from Harvard pushed back on that view, finding that a high-fat diet can boost the body\'s ability to burn fuel and can support weight loss.\n\nFood has the power to heal many long-term diseases. It can work cheaper, better, and faster than any drug, and the only side effects are good ones, as Mark Hyman has written. Beans and grains are the next piece of the puzzle. The belief that beans are a harmless source of protein does not hold up. Beans can be hard to digest, can spark inflammation, and can trigger problems for people with autoimmune conditions. Their high starch content can also push up blood sugar in people with type 1 or type 2 diabetes.\n\nBeans and grains only became everyday foods after farming spread. Oatmeal is a popular breakfast, but it is often misunderstood. Oats carry fiber and carbs that break down quickly, which can drive up insulin and lead to weight gain. That is why a bowl of oatmeal can leave you hungry again before lunch. A grain has three parts. Bran offers fiber, germ holds the nutrients, and endosperm is mostly starch. The starch part is what spikes blood sugar. Granola bars are no better than candy in that regard. The takeaway is that neither beans nor grains are required in your diet, so eat them in moderation.\n\nNuts and seeds close out the list. Pistachios have a real track record of helping with erectile dysfunction. Walnuts and almonds can help lower the risk of breast cancer. In general, nuts and seeds are great for restoring energy. Their fats can quiet hunger and support healthy digestion. Many people turn to nuts when they want to lose weight. Pecans, walnuts, hazelnuts, pistachios, and almonds also carry antioxidants, which can protect the heart and lower the risk of cancer.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Artificial additives put your health at risk',
        text: 'It is hard to find vegetables grown without pesticides or chocolate made without emulsifiers. Processed food, weed killers, bug sprays, genetically modified crops, antibiotics, and chemical additives all quietly threaten health. The four biggest offenders deserve a closer look.\n\nUnhealthy processed food leads the way. Fresh olives straight from the tree taste sharp and a bit bitter. People cure them with salt, water, or lye to make them pleasant. That is what processing is. But not every method is safe. Dr. Hyman recommends avoiding foods that contain the following. Ingredients you cannot pronounce. Skip anything with words you cannot read. Brand new products that did not exist a generation ago. Ask an older relative if they have ever heard of it. High fructose corn syrup, which is mostly corn starch and about 76 percent carbohydrate. Hydrogenated oils, where liquid fat is turned solid, creating trans fat that raises the risk of heart disease. Anything pushed hard on TV, since loud ads that promise wild results are a red flag.\n\nIf a product has more than five ingredients, it is usually safer to leave it on the shelf. Pesticides and herbicides come next. Farm produce is sprayed with toxic chemicals meant to kill pests. Over time, those chemicals can lead to long-term illness. Choosing organic fruits and vegetables lowers the risk.\n\nGenetically modified organisms, or GMOs, are the third item. Scientists say GMOs are needed to feed the world and protect the environment, but the long-term effects on health are still unclear. The safe play is to choose organic food and skip GMOs when you can.\n\nAntibiotics are the fourth. When bacteria face antibiotics again and again, they grow resistant. Farmers have to use higher doses, and the industry often puts profit ahead of safety. The smart move is to take charge of what you eat. Skip mass-produced meat and poultry, and choose organic produce. That habit can help protect your immune system from these hidden threats.\n\nA bit of trivia. Salt was once very costly and rare. Widespread access to salt changed the course of cooking and food production.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A healthy life starts with a clean body',
        text: 'Almost everyone wants food that tastes good and supports health, but only a few take the time to study nutrition. Even a diet that seems balanced can hide risky foods or risky combinations. Sometimes the right move is to change how you eat, not just what you eat. A sudden shift in diet can bring tiredness, hunger, and mood swings. The shift has to be done the right way.\n\nThe first step to consider is a detox program. You would not load expensive software onto a computer that is already infected. The system has to be cleared first. The body fights off toxins every day, and most of them come from food and drink. It makes sense to reset the system before changing eating habits for good.\n\nThe detox phase should run for ten days. The main steps are as follows. Stay away from foods that spark inflammation, such as cheap packaged products, gluten, refined oils, soft drinks, and fruits like bananas, oranges, and pineapples. Focus on whole clean foods. Vegetables should make up the largest share of the day, along with high-quality meat, fish, nuts, seeds, herbs, and spices. Build a habit of taking supplements, since multivitamins, omega-3, magnesium, and zinc help round out a balanced diet. Move the body and rest well. Changing habits is hard, so the nervous system and willpower need support. Yoga, meditation, and time with loved ones lower stress and lift motivation. Exercise and time outside boost energy and mood. Good sleep lets the body recharge for the next day.\n\nA higher grocery bill today can mean a lower medical bill later. After the detox, it is time to build a personal menu. Skip any food with a long ingredient list. Check the source of meat and fish, and ease back on them if they are the main item in your meals. Cut out any food that your body reacts to. This way of eating lets you stay in tune with your own needs and care for your health.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Final thoughts on food and health',
        text: 'The saying "you are what you eat" is a strong starting point for a healthy diet. When it comes to food, it is fine to be picky. Listen to your gut, your taste buds, and the way your body reacts, and choose the best products. Your life depends on it.\n\nNot every food has to be organic, but pick the ones that are as close to nature as possible. Cooking at home is worth another try. Homemade meals take more time, but they are far healthier than ready-to-cook food. Even a burger made with local meat, home-grown vegetables, and a sauce from organic ingredients can be a solid and healthy dinner.\n\nRead every label. If you cannot pronounce a word on the list, leave the product on the shelf. Be wary of foods that are heavily marketed. Good food does not need a loud ad campaign. It will take time to change old habits, but the change leads to a better life.\n\nA simple exercise to try. Take a fresh look at your kitchen. If ready-to-cook meals, sweets, and bread fill most of the space, it is time for a change. Start small. Write down the five least healthy products in your kitchen, like cheap meat, chips, or candy bars. Think of healthier swaps for each one. Thinly sliced potatoes baked with a little salt make a fine replacement for chips. Next time you shop, leave those five items in the store. Repeat the same exercise a week or two later, and slowly most of your food will be replaced with better options.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'fooled-by-randomness.json': {
    base: { id: 'fooled-by-randomness', title: 'Fooled by Randomness', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781658688559 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Luck hides more than people think',
        text: 'The stock market shows this pattern in a clear way. Some investors get labeled as gifted simply because they have been on a winning streak. Their good results get chalked up to skill when chance played a much larger part.\n\nSome fields do require real skill to succeed. A long career in medicine or law does not fall into your lap by luck. Training and ability matter there.\n\nThe stock market is different. Real rules are hard to pin down, and chance drives a lot of the outcome. Because of the built-in randomness of markets, an investor with no skill can post the same returns as a skilled one over many years.\n\nIn fact, 10,000 investors who pick stocks at random have about a 45 percent chance of finishing a year in the green. That number hints at a strange truth. You could do just as well by flipping a coin.\n\nFrom that crowd of 10,000 random investors, close to 200 will log a profit every year for five years running. People will start to call them talented, but in truth they just guessed and got lucky.\n\nOver the long run, the truth comes out. Many of those lucky investors will one day lose everything in a single bad quarter, wiping out years of gains.\n\nThe rest of this summary looks at how we mistake randomness for cause and effect, why we keep underestimating chance, and what we can do about it.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Change is the one constant',
        text: 'Empirical science builds its ideas through a process called induction. It depends on what people observe. Picture someone who sees hundreds of goats and notices they are all black. They might conclude that every goat is black.\n\nThe moment a goat of a different color shows up, that conclusion falls apart. The problem of induction says that no theory can ever be proven right. It can only be proven wrong. So theories keep shifting as new evidence rolls in.\n\nThis view applies to investing as well. Any theory you trust can break at any time. Build that possibility into the shape of your portfolio. Using the past to predict the future is a recipe for disaster.\n\nHuman choice keeps changing the world, and adaptation is constant. As people adjust to new realities, business changes too. The patterns that seemed solid in the past will shift, which removes the very effect you expected to see.\n\nMost people pick the familiar over the new. Evolution shows that even unfit creatures sometimes beat the odds. Survival of the fittest only describes the average outcome, not the only possible one.\n\nThe QWERTY keyboard is a good example. It was built to stop keys from jamming on old typewriters. Once typing technology improved, no one wanted to switch. A better layout could have won, but QWERTY had already become the norm.\n\nThis is called a path dependent outcome. Some products stay on top simply because they crossed a tipping point. Microsoft got big because people bought what their friends and coworkers were using. The choice had little to do with quality.\n\nTipping points are nonlinear, which makes them hard to predict. A tiny input can spark a huge shift. The truth is that people often give up just before they would have broken through. The extra mile is uneven for everyone. Some hit it fast, others take much longer, and there is no standard rule to follow. Chance plays a role here too.\n\nNo matter how sharp our choices or how well we play the odds, randomness always has the last word, as Nassim Nicholas Taleb has observed.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Context shapes how we see outcomes',
        text: 'We live in an age of nonstop information. At the same time, our minds are not built to weigh the probabilities that come with all that data. To keep up, we fall back on rules that oversimplify things and on assumptions that cloud our judgment.\n\nThe result is a steady stream of biases. Psychologists have shown that we carry many kinds of biases, and they keep us from seeing situations clearly. Attribution bias, for example, is why we credit hard work for our wins and blame bad luck for our losses.\n\nThe path that leads to an outcome shapes how we feel about it. This is called path dependence. Losses sting more than wins of the same size. Imagine winning $50,000 today and losing $40,000 tomorrow. That result feels worse than simply winning $10,000 tomorrow with no losses along the way. The end number is the same, but the path makes the feeling different.\n\nWhen the first idea in a chain of thoughts sets the tone, those beliefs are path dependent. Path dependence also keeps us tied to old opinions even when fresh evidence pushes back. We repeat old arguments and dig in rather than update our views.\n\nParents can fall into the same trap. They have invested years in their children and find it hard to step back. That habit can backfire. The healthy move is to contradict yourself on purpose and update your views. Remind yourself that your children are adults now and can make their own calls.\n\nA mistake is not something to judge after the fact, but in light of the information available until that point, as Nassim Nicholas Taleb has written.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Emotions can lift or sink our choices',
        text: 'Decision making gets easier when emotions are in the mix. When two options look equally good, pure logic leaves you stuck. An emotional nudge, even a small one, is often what tips the scale.\n\nNeurobiologists have found that feelings come before logic. Our rational mind is really just looking for reasons to justify the feelings we already have. Reason is not the strongest force in the room. Being aware of this is important when a clear-headed choice is needed. An investor, for example, has to learn to set emotions aside so that impulse does not lead to losses.\n\nPast experience is of little use when the future is up for grabs. Investors keep fooling themselves into thinking the market will not crash, or that they will see a crash coming. Psychologists call this hindsight bias. We look at past events and build a mental model to predict when they will happen again. The problem is that the model only works for those exact past conditions. If a new situation looks nothing like the past, the model fails, and we are fooled by randomness.\n\nIn the markets, traders use backtesters to build trading rules. They comb through past data and design rules that would have worked back then. Modern computers make this kind of analysis powerful. But the past results came from chance as much as skill. Those rules may not work in the next market cycle.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Caught off guard by the unexpected',
        text: 'The French writer Henry de Montherlant, a nobleman, chose to end his life after learning that a degenerative condition was robbing him of his sight. His choice clashes with the Stoic view, which pushes for something different. Stoics teach that we should take charge of our fate, especially when outcomes are uncertain. We always have a choice, to give up or to accept what life puts in front of us. In a world of randomness, our power shows up in how we respond to small events and big ones alike.\n\nUnexpected events are constant. Hedge funds often blame their losses on surprises their models never planned for. Their models fail because they leave no room for chance. A single random event can wreck an expected outcome. These rare events get ignored in most data analysis because people assume they will not happen.\n\nThe COVID-19 pandemic is a clear example of an unexpected event that shook the global economy. Investors are easy prey for such surprises. A model that delivered small wins in the past gets scaled up, leaving the investor wide open to a sudden crash.\n\nIt is healthy to be open to serendipity, as long as it does no harm. Outside of investing, chance can be a positive force. Art and poetry, for example, can turn ordinary words into something beautiful. Science and finance, on the other hand, need precision and have little patience for flowery language. So we are fooled by randomness in the first case and need cold logic in the second.\n\nEven when we follow every rule, we can still be hit by harmful randomness. A person who eats well, exercises, and gets enough sleep can still get cancer, while a chain smoker might live a long life and pass quietly in their sleep.\n\nStoicism is the right response to harmful randomness. We have to be brave and face reality without fear. Self-pity, blame, and self-destruction do not help. The better path is a quiet kind of dignity. Show wisdom and courage when misfortune arrives.\n\nA point worth remembering. Our response to randomness is the only real control we have over random events in our lives.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The media adds a lot of noise',
        text: 'Checking the news and stock reports every day pays off very little. Social media is full of false and useless stories.\n\nSorting through useless news to find useful news costs more time than it gives back. Stock prices move around for no clear reason. Trying to explain every wiggle is a waste, since the movement often breaks the rules we think prices should follow. Prices only make sense over long stretches. Short term moves are mostly random noise.\n\nAn investor who checks the portfolio often feels more pleasure and more pain than one who checks once a year. Someone who checks every minute may enjoy about 60,688 minutes of pleasure in a year and about 60,271 minutes of pain. Someone who checks once a year for 20 years can expect 19 out of 20 years to feel good.\n\nEven when the end result is the same, the investor who checks all the time ends up emotionally drained, since losses sting more than wins satisfy.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Final thoughts on randomness',
        text: 'Randomness fools everyone, yet we tend to call it fate. A lucky streak gets turned into a story about skill. The world keeps changing, and those changes overturn yesterday\'s theories. The best does not always win, and even careful living cannot prevent disaster.\n\nWe fail to grasp the weight of randomness because of biases that have built up over time. Our thinking is often tied to a single context and relies on rough rules of thumb. Emotions can cloud our choices, but they can also point us in the right direction. The habit of looking for patterns and explanations in past events makes our predictions of the future weak. The past rarely repeats itself, and we are bad at judging rare events.\n\nTo live with randomness, we should enjoy the harmless kind and face the harmful kind with courage, dignity, and responsibility. Resist the pull of random noise from media and the markets.\n\nA small exercise to try. Over the next two weeks, make a point of making decisions that are not driven by emotion. Then check the results and see how it goes.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'forever-strong-a-new-science-based-strategy-for-aging-well.json': {
    base: { id: 'forever-strong-a-new-science-based-strategy-for-aging-well', title: 'Forever Strong', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781650637200 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Growing old while staying young',
        text: 'You have probably seen the jokes online. There is Jennifer Lopez on stage in her fifties, full of energy, while a twenty-something can barely stand up after washing their hair. The jokes land because they touch a real fear.\n\nMany people feel the aches of aging in their thirties, a time when life is supposed to feel light and easy. The basics are well known. Eat well, move your body, sleep enough, and keep stress in check. Even so, plenty of people still find themselves in the doctor\'s office during the best years of their lives.\n\nThe trouble is that most diets and workout plans are built around losing fat, not building health. People pour willpower, discipline, and time into the wrong goal, and the effort goes to waste. The truth is that strong and flexible muscles are the armor that keeps you active and healthy for decades.\n\nBurning fat is not the same as building muscle. Focus on muscle, and the fat will follow. This summary walks through simple principles that help you stay healthy and active as the years pass. Give your future self the gift of strength and energy so you can stay independent, enjoy your hobbies, spend time with the people you love, and even dance at a grandchild\'s wedding when you are 80.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A crash diet can hurt you more than it helps',
        text: 'Most of us have been there. You break another diet with a bag of chips or a bowl of popcorn, then regret it. Or you log miles on a treadmill trying to lose the last ten pounds, and they will not budge. The flood of advice can wear you down and leave you confused and worn out.\n\nThe classic crash diet, which counts calories, restricts food groups, and treats certain foods as villains, does not work in the long run. Eventually, the cravings win and you go back to old habits, often eating more than before. The weight comes back, and often with interest.\n\nIf you pick the easy road, life gets hard in the end. If you pick the hard road, life gets easier, as Dr. Gabrielle Lyon has written.\n\nThe other trap is endless training that only aims to burn fat instead of building muscle. You do Zumba or run for hours a week to burn calories, and the result is that you feel hungrier and weaker. The wrong mix of food and exercise drains your energy.\n\nFocus on building your body rather than shrinking it. The Lyon Protocol balances fat loss with muscle growth, and muscle makes up about 40 percent of body mass. Strong muscle helps you jump and run when you are young, and it helps you get off the couch when you are ninety. The number on the scale can fool you into losing the real prize, which is muscle-driven strength.\n\nIt is easy to feel fine even when you sit all day, skip workouts, and eat whatever is around. But age-related problems like Alzheimer\'s, heart disease, low energy, and diabetes are tied to weak, unused muscles. Your body weight might be fine while your health quietly slips.\n\nA small change helps. Stand at your desk instead of sitting, or walk to the office with light hand weights. The Lyon Protocol lets you build health on your own terms. Let\'s get started.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Choosing the future over the present',
        text: 'For centuries, people have searched for a cure for aging. Alchemists tried to brew a potion of youth that could stretch life or grant immortality. Modern science has not found a way to live forever, but it does offer tools to slow aging down.\n\nThe ultimate life hack is hard work, as Dr. Gabrielle Lyon has said. The answer lies in muscle. It is the one part of the body you can train and shape directly. You cannot train your liver or pancreas, but you can build muscle, which supports every organ and helps prevent many diseases. Strength training, for example, can improve the way your body uses food. Calories go toward energy and repair rather than getting stored as fat.\n\nMany people blame slow metabolism and low energy on getting older. There is some truth to that, but not at age thirty. Sitting still and eating the wrong foods starves the body of nutrients while piling on weight. It is far easier to grab a cookie or stream a show than to head to the gym. You do deserve rest, but you also deserve a healthy body.\n\nDon\'t give up on your dreams when life shifts. Adapt and find a new way to reach your goal.\n\nSo how do you put your future self ahead of your cravings? Social psychologist Dr. Emily Balcetis offers three steps. First, dream big. Sit in a quiet place and picture the person you want to become. What habits do they have? What does their day look like? Second, plan. Note the steps you can take today to become that future person. Third, foresee failure. Knowing your weak spots is power. If you want to watch a movie, set it up on the treadmill and walk while you watch.\n\nFinally, think about what happens if you do not change. If you keep eating and living the way you do today, will you have the energy to do the things you love? Picture yourself on that path. If you do not like the picture, take heart. You still have time to rewrite it.'
      },
      {
        title: 'An eating plan for life',
        text: 'Protein is arguably the most important piece of any diet. It carries the amino acids that support the body and keep organs working well. Many people are quietly protein-starved because their diet leans on calories and fats instead of protein.\n\nLow protein drives cravings for sugar and carbs, and it leaves you tired and cranky by the afternoon. Instead of feeding the body what it really needs, many people reach for cup after cup of coffee. Caffeine gives a short lift and then fades. Too much of it can backfire in the long run.\n\nFirst, you put in the work for your nutrition, and then nutrition starts working for you, as the saying goes. The Lyon Protocol puts protein at the center of the diet. Carbs and fats are interchangeable. You can have more of one and less of the other, but never trade protein for extra fat or carbs. Here are the core rules for a sustainable and healthy diet.\n\nTake one gram of protein for each pound of your goal body weight. For most people, each meal should have 30 to 50 grams of protein. Sources vary in quality and calories, though. Beef and chicken give you more amino acids per calorie than plants do. A chicken breast with 25 grams of protein has about half the calories of black beans with the same protein, and about a quarter of the calories of quinoa with the same protein.\n\nPair carbs with protein in a one to one ratio and lean on vegetables and berries for most of your carbs. Keep grains and starches to about 30 grams a day. Spend the rest of your calories on healthy fats. Set your total calories based on your goal. To lose weight, eat 12 to 13 calories for each pound of your target weight. If you want to weigh 140 pounds, aim for about 1,820 calories a day. Start the day with a protein-rich meal. Breakfast should carry about a third of your daily protein. Pick eggs, meat, or fish over cereal or toast.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Train to live, age with strength',
        text: 'Training your muscles is like putting on armor for a long battle. It protects you from dying too young. The fear of getting bulky turns many women away from strength training, and that fear can be costly.\n\nAlong with a thoughtful diet, the Lyon Protocol comes with a clear workout plan. It is not about reaching a certain look. It is about a longer, healthier life. The earlier you start, the better.\n\nLet your health be the goal, not society\'s beauty standards. So what kind of training should you do? Everyone needs two types of activity. Resistance training builds and strengthens muscle by breaking it down and letting it repair. It includes dumbbell work, push-ups, sit-ups, and crunches. Endurance training boosts the heart and lungs, like running, swimming, biking, or full-body cardio. High-intensity interval training, or HIIT, mixes short bursts of hard work with short rests, which is great for busy schedules.\n\nThe right amount of weekly exercise depends on your life, body, schedule, goals, and fitness level. A beginner with less than two months of training should aim for about 150 minutes of moderate aerobic exercise a week, along with two days of full-body resistance training. A more advanced lifter with at least a year of training should aim for at least 150 minutes of vigorous cardio a week and four to six days of full-body strength training.\n\nKeep your training goals SMART. Specific, like "I want to get ready for ski season." Measurable, like "I will lose ten pounds." Actionable, like "I can work out four days a week." Realistic, like "I can do only low-intensity cardio twice a week." Timely, like "I will stick with the plan for the next three months."\n\nA point worth knowing. Richard Osman has written detective novels about a group of older friends who solve crimes and call themselves the Thursday Murder Club. The books inspire people to stay active and to thrive into their eighties and nineties.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Make your surroundings work for you',
        text: 'A touching ad tells the story of an older man who decides one morning to start exercising. He looks at a wall covered in photos and remembers his younger, fitter self. He almost gives up, then puts a photo in front of him for motivation. To his neighbors\' surprise, he works out every morning and his shape improves. On Christmas, he dresses up and heads to his daughter\'s dinner. The family learns the real reason for his effort. He wanted to be strong enough to lift his granddaughter so she could place a star on top of the tree. Her photo was the spark that kept him going.\n\nEveryone can find a trigger that keeps them going. The trigger is not a beach body for summer or a smaller dress size. Those goals rarely last. Real perseverance comes from meaningful targets that grow from within. Common examples include wanting to feel healthier after too many sick days, getting stronger for a future pregnancy or recovery, protecting the body and mind from conditions that run in the family, and getting ready for retirement.\n\nBuild goals that last. Visualize them often, especially when energy fades or life gets messy. Fit training into your life in a way that supports you, not the other way around.\n\nYou can also use your environment to your advantage. Put visual reminders around the house and office, like props, stickers, and photos, to stay on track in moments of doubt. Find company. The support of friends and family matters most in hard moments. Clear out temptations. Remove junk food from the kitchen and distractions from your day. Picture the result. Spend a few minutes visualizing your goal. Picture yourself hiking any mountain, playing soccer with your grandchildren, or biking through Italian vineyards in your seventies.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Final thoughts on aging well',
        text: 'Most people care about looking good, but few think about their health and overall wellness until something goes wrong. The best way to prevent disease is to act first. Build your muscle armor now. Resistance training and a protein-rich diet can build a strong body that lets you chase your dreams, meet your duties, and enjoy life at any age. Train your muscles now, and they will be there for you later.\n\nA small set of steps to try. Start weighing your food. It only matters at first, when you need to learn the calories and nutrients in your usual portions. Plan your meals for the week. Never go grocery shopping hungry, or you will end up with food you do not need. Keep a stash of healthy snacks nearby for those moments when you want a treat during a movie.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'four-hundred-souls.json': {
    base: { id: 'four-hundred-souls', title: 'Four Hundred Souls', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781658783076 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'The long shadow of slavery and resistance',
        text: 'A great deal of the struggle Black Americans face today can be traced back to slavery. The stories that make up the heavy record of Black struggle all begin in 1619.\n\nSlavery is a stain on American history, and it still shapes the country today. About 400 years ago, people who wanted cheap labor opened this dark chapter. Colonizers sailed to Africa, took captives by force, and shipped them across the ocean to work on huge plantations. That act set the tone for relations between white and Black Americans for centuries.\n\nLong after the law ended slavery, deep hatred for Black people remained. The motive behind slavery may have started as money, but its real engine was racism. Racism is the broader unfair treatment of races different from the captors. That bias has not gone away, and it drove a long stretch of abuse and violence against the Black community even after slavery ended. The fight against racism gave rise to leaders like Malcolm X and Martin Luther King Jr., who set a new standard for equality.\n\nBlack people joined forces, refusing to be the permanent target of oppression because of their skin color. Their main weapon in the 1960s was the civil rights movement.\n\nIt often seems that the white world feels threatened wherever Black bodies appear, haunted by the ghosts of sins it has never paid for, as Robert Jones Jr. has written.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Segregation kept the pressure on after slavery ended',
        text: 'When the 13th Amendment ended slavery in 1865, the Black community expected to live as free people. It did not happen. The horrors of slavery had settled into the culture, and oppression waited around every corner. Racism was everywhere, and it led to violence and persecution. Segregation became a new cage. Black people still lived under its weight even after formal slavery ended.\n\nThe end of slavery did not end the oppression and discrimination. Segregation is the act of setting a group apart from the rest. In practice, it meant that Black people were barred from many places and from mixing with the larger white population. The mistreatment did not stop there. The Black community was treated as less than human. The idea was to keep Black people from "corrupting" white people, and it justified a system of separation that offered no real path to equality.\n\nSegregation turned into open hunting, lynching, and other cruel practices. The pressure forced Black families into survival mode. They had no choice but to band together.\n\nRacism is a dangerous force. It puts its victims in real danger. The Black community has come a long way, but it took a great deal of work, blood, sweat, and tears to get here. The fight for racial equality still faces many hurdles. The survival of an average Black person is not guaranteed in a system that stacks the deck against them in schools, jobs, and prisons.\n\nThe Christianity that blessed white supremacy did not fade when slavery ended, as Ibram X. Kendi has written.\n\nA point worth knowing. Across the Atlantic Slave Trade, from about 1526 to 1867, about 12.5 million enslaved people were shipped from Africa, and about 10.7 million arrived in the Americas. The trade was likely the deadliest long-distance migration in human history.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Slavery was not a choice, and the journey was brutal',
        text: 'When Black people were forced to migrate to the strange new land of the United States, the adjustment was violent. In the chains of slavery, there was no time to "stop and smell the flowers." They were dropped straight into a society that hated them.\n\nThe people they had to deal with were too locked into their own oppressive past to see them as human. The journey to the United States was not a choice, and there was nowhere else to go. After freedom came, they had to learn how to live, thrive, and build in a country that wanted nothing from them. The feeling of belonging nowhere and being hated for simply existing made it hard to find a purpose or live peacefully in a divided society.\n\nEven after slavery ended, white people kept showing racism and hatred, and the Black community felt more isolated and lost. The Black community had to piece itself back together. Their old identities had been stripped away, lost, and left behind in Africa. Who were they now? Not Africans. They had been taken from their land and dropped in a foreign one. They needed a fresh identity, and that identity had to fill the hunger for place, purpose, and community.\n\nThe only response to a system that tries to kill and erase you is to fight back and build a new identity for yourself. The path to self-discovery was full of obstacles, but it led to a rich new history. The deep roots of Black music, fashion, and art rose to the surface and became a banner for the movement. The search for a new identity led the Black community to blend their African heritage with their American one. They were no longer "Africans" or "Americans." They were "African Americans," a name that tried to unite the two halves.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Cultural oppression was a quieter form of abuse, but it cut just as deep',
        text: 'Slavery was over, but the Black community was still a target. The new attack was cultural, and the goal was to erase their culture entirely. The idea was to "white-wash" their heritage and force them to take on a way of life that was not theirs.\n\nRacism is so deeply harmful that it attacks the present and tries to erase the past. Losing your culture, or having it taken from you, is like a small death. Culture can support and guide you through the hardest times. It gives a sense of community and beauty. Without a link to your cultural roots, you can keep living, but a piece of you is missing. Racism says that your race is lesser and should be wiped out, along with anything your race has built. In essence, it is a kind of cultural genocide. Black people have faced a slow, sometimes violent erasure of their culture for centuries. Despite every effort to erase their music, art, and fashion, they managed to keep it alive through the hardship.\n\nThe Black community faced harsher forms of oppression as the years went on, whether political, social, or cultural. They kept growing even in that hostile environment, which speaks to the strength of the community. It also speaks to the power of community. Their endless fight was for the right to live, to work, and to enjoy the fruits of their own labor.\n\nThe freedom fighters who led the charge did so to protect Black lives and to preserve and grow Black culture. That culture was central to Black history, so it had to be defended at all costs. The activists tried to lift up those who were too afraid or too lost to claim their own origins. Many Black people had been living in fear, and that fear had brought a great darkness. The darkness drowned hope and threatened to kill their sense of humanity and community.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Black artists, writers, and musicians changed the world',
        text: 'As Black people kept searching for self-discovery, they found a deep well of talent in the performing arts, music, theater, dance, sports, and politics. They had huge reserves of energy and potential, and they poured them into reviving their culture. The culture they had been searching for became a true gold mine.\n\nThey needed to take back their voice as a community, and the arts gave them a place to do it. The people who drove this cultural boom brought it to a wider audience. After years of pain, suffering, and forced change, they filled the world with life, light, and beauty.\n\nMusic had always been a way for the Black community to release pain and ease suffering. Now it became a way to step into the spotlight. From gospel to jazz to reggae, the rhythms and lyrics carried a fierce love of life and a vision of a brighter future. Music pulled the community together under a shared sense of beauty, and it still stands as a central form of expression for African Americans today.\n\nThe world got to see real art, rich and varied, born of the many struggles that had torn at the Black community. The performing arts became a tool for change and a lifeline for those who had been left behind. Art gave relief to people who were suffering because of the color of their skin.\n\nMusic and the arts were essential tools for bringing the community\'s struggles to the front of the public mind. Creative expression became an escape for many. Young Black people rediscovered their talent and a hunger to rise above hatred and discrimination to a place of financial and mental stability. Art was a way to push back, refusing to bow to someone else\'s authority. It gave them a voice, and with that voice they could share the pain and the experience of being Black in America. Countless Black artists have become world famous because they chose to use their gifts.'
      },
      {
        title: 'With reinvention came hope',
        text: 'The Black identity has moved through a painful stage of formation, but the need to keep reinventing it in American society is still alive. African Americans have shifted the story of their history in real ways and have built a meaningful power shift. From the civil rights movement to the protests of recent years, they have made sure their voice sits at the front of American politics. A new dawn in Black America has begun, and the fight continues today.\n\nWith the end of legal oppression came a clear need to reinvent the Black identity. Bowing your head and letting oppression win is no longer the way. The Black community has grown into a force that can demand its fair share. Today, more Black people sit in important government positions than ever before. Barack Obama became President of the United States in 2008, showing once again that Black people can drive change in society and take leading roles in the country\'s most important institutions.\n\nTo fight a system that wants to push you down, the smart move is often to step inside it and reshape it from within. Their ancestors had no choice but to serve the white citizens who ran the government. Now, more Black people are demanding better treatment from the government in every area, from education to healthcare. There has been a real shift in perspective, and there is more hope for change than ever before.\n\nRacism is a stain on the fabric of history, and it has to be fought on every front. Do not be fooled. The effects of racism still linger, and there is more work to do. The only way to live free of the poison of racism and racial injustice is to tear down any system that places one set of people above another because of their race or skin color. Black people in the United States are not just asking for better treatment. They are reshaping the social, political, and cultural structure of the country and claiming their rightful place.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Final thoughts on the long road of Black history',
        text: 'Black people have had to push through a long history of oppression and persecution. First, it was slavery. Today, it is the constant threat of racism. Years of discrimination have only made the community stronger. The African American population has shown that it can find a way to thrive no matter the conditions.\n\nThe trials, starting from the moment their ancestors were captured and brought to a foreign land and stretching to the trials of today, would break almost any group. They would steal faith, fight, and hope. Yet Black people keep surviving and growing, and the trend is only moving upward.\n\nThe takeaway is that a better life and future are possible if you keep the fight alive. During slavery, Black people had little on their side, not the numbers and not the support. They dug deep and found the strength to build a life in a strange land they had to call home.\n\nRacism has played the largest role in this tragedy, and it is still causing harm far beyond America. The fight against hatred and discrimination has to go on without pause. Racism is not just a threat to its victims. It can also poison the minds of those who carry it, robbing them of a chance to live a full, hate-free life.\n\nA small exercise to try. Take a moment to read about the history of slavery in America, and learn about key figures like Malcolm X. These leaders helped push the change that brought the freedoms Black people enjoy today. A good starting point is "Uncomfortable Conversations with a Black Man." You can search the Headway library for it.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'frames-of-mind.json': {
    base: { id: 'frames-of-mind', title: 'Frames of Mind', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781658913866 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'A single IQ number misses what the mind can really do',
        text: 'In modern Western culture, many people treat intelligence as a single trait that can be measured with one number, the Intelligence Quotient, or IQ. But the brain runs many kinds of intelligence in relative isolation, which makes a single score a poor summary of what the mind can do.\n\nAnything worth teaching can be shown in many ways by drawing on multiple intelligences. Dr. Gardner groups the many forms of human intelligence into seven kinds. They are linguistic, musical, logical-mathematical, spatial, bodily-kinesthetic, intrapersonal, and interpersonal. His theory says that once we accept the existence of many intelligences, it is easier to understand why some people have certain talents and others do not. Knowing that musical intelligence exists, for example, makes it easy to see why singers like Beethoven or Andrea Bocelli have such a sharp command of voice and sound.\n\nBrain scientists and geneticists are mapping the wide variety of human abilities. Computer programmers are building systems that are intelligent in their own ways. Educators are starting to accept that their students have different strengths and weaknesses, as Dr. Howard Gardner has noted. More research into multiple intelligences could make it possible to design new tests that spot a child\'s strengths and limits, which would help teachers draw out the best in every student.\n\nThis summary is a good fit for scientists, philosophers, and anyone curious about human social behavior and emotion.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The current view of intelligence holds the mind back',
        text: 'The modern view of intelligence has spread so far that it sounds like a tidy list of measurable traits. It works well as a way to describe how a person thrives in a given field, and it is especially useful in the areas Dr. Gardner has studied. He laid out a list of brain abilities to back up the idea of multiple intelligences.\n\nWith the right encouragement, enrichment, and teaching, most people can grow their intellect to a solid level. Gardner admits that his list does not cover every possible angle, since he sees intelligence as a whole with many levels of analysis. A complete list would only be possible if he focused on a single field of study, like neurophysiology.\n\nWhy try to define intelligence at all when it is relative and shaped by so many factors? For example, the measured intelligence of someone in a poor country is likely to score lower than that of someone in a wealthy country. Education, poverty, and other factors all leave a deep mark on test results. Intelligence varies from person to person, but it is still possible to draw broad patterns from many examples. The chapters that follow explain the kinds of intelligence we have and how they can help us understand our own minds.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Many intelligences can help people reach their full potential',
        text: 'Researchers do not agree on whether intelligence is inherited. Some experts say genetics can account for up to 80 percent of cognitive scores, while others put the share closer to 20 percent. A few even argue that IQ cannot be drawn as a straight line at all.\n\nGiven that, should we drop the language that treats talent as a fixed inheritance? We can say some people are born with the right wiring for a given skill, but that does not mean the skill will appear. Someone could be born with the ability to play chess well, but without a chessboard, that ability will go nowhere. Put that person in a place where chess is everywhere and the talent can bloom fast.\n\nFrom a biological view, the environment can help a person reach a high level of skill in certain areas. The science of inheritance is complex, and it is hard to separate what came from genes from what came from the world around us.\n\nKnowing when and where to learn is key to mastering a new skill. Canalization and plasticity are two ideas from neurobiology that help us understand how the brain works. Canalization is when a biological system grows in a predictable way. The human nervous system, for example, starts to mature in the neural tube of an embryo and then moves into place to form the brain and spine.\n\nMany environmental factors shape development, which is called plasticity. Even if a child\'s brain is hurt in the first year of life, they can still learn to communicate later. Language is one of the most flexible parts of the brain. As we age, however, brain plasticity drops, which is why an adult who loses the left hemisphere can struggle with language.\n\nThe theory of multiple intelligences matters because it can help society get the most out of every child\'s brain. Teachers, for example, can use early knowledge of a student\'s interests to design a better learning path.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Linguistic intelligence means a deep feel for how language works',
        text: 'Language comprehension is one of the most studied kinds of intelligence from a neurobiological point of view. Researchers know a good deal about how language skills develop, from a baby\'s first words to the long sentences a child can use by age four or five.\n\nPeople speak many languages across every culture, so those with high language intelligence can express themselves in words and in body more easily. The language used by songwriters, composers, and poets matters a great deal to them. They pay close attention to the many shades of meaning in a word, which makes it easier to write with simple words in fresh ways. They also think about how a word can echo through other lines and which words sound good together.\n\nPoetry is just one use of language ability. Rhetoric, for example, leans on language to persuade people to act, which is what politicians do to sway public opinion. Linguistic intelligence can also help people understand ideas and metaphors, among other things.\n\nMost people\'s language skills live in the left hemisphere of the brain. Damage to specific parts of that hemisphere can knock out certain language skills. People with damage to Broca\'s area in the frontal lobe, for example, often write in a style that echoes Ernest Hemingway\'s iceberg theory, with a simple surface hiding a deeper meaning. Linguistic intelligence is a key part of communication. Conversations and speeches become clearer when people have a strong grip on their language.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Musical intelligence is about sensitivity to the qualities of sound',
        text: 'Most research links musical intelligence to a person\'s ability to communicate through speech and sound. We can sharpen our musical intelligence by learning about harmonic tones in different ways.\n\nMusically gifted people hear and spot patterns very quickly. Their brains think in terms of style. They pick out patterns in new music to help them learn. They also look for patterns in the way people speak, like lyrics and rhymes. Musically intelligent people have a strong sense of what music is really about.\n\nMelodic composition is the peak of musical intelligence in the same way that poetry is the peak of linguistic intelligence. Even though only a small number of people will ever work as composers, many people can grasp the basic structure of music. They can then match pieces with similar patterns and rhythms.\n\nMusic, like language, depends heavily on the auditory system. The way the brain handles and stores pitch is different from the way it handles other sounds, like speech. In her research, psychologist Diana Deutsch asked volunteers to remember a series of tones. She then added other sounds to the original tones to keep them engaged. When the added sounds were made of many tones, the error rate was about 40 percent. When she replaced the tones with words or numbers, the error rate dropped to just 2 percent. The takeaway is that skill with sound and rhythm alone is not enough to build musical intelligence. Mastery of words and numbers also plays a big part.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Logical-mathematical intelligence is about conceptual thinking',
        text: 'Logical-mathematical intelligence is the ability to analyze problems in a logical way, to do math, and to detect scientific patterns. It also includes the ability to build equations and proofs, run calculations, and work through abstract ideas.\n\nSwiss psychologist Jean Piaget laid out an early version of this idea. As a child, he was given a circle of objects in front of him. He counted them and got 10. He then pointed to the objects in a different order and counted 10 again. After many such tests, he saw that the number 10 stood for the whole set, no matter what order the objects were in.\n\nMathematical intelligence helps with abstract, symbolic thinking, step-by-step reasoning, and both inductive and deductive thinking, and it boosts overall brain performance. Because of his early tests, Piaget understood numbers from a young age, and the process leaned on his logical-mathematical skills. The first step was interacting with the physical world, which grows more abstract with time and eventually crosses into logical and scientific territory.\n\nWhen young mathematicians apply their knowledge to real problems, they often face a long chain of math statements. Remembering the links in the chain can help, but mathematicians are not known for their memory. Their grasp of the logical links between statements and the overall meaning is what helps them solve hard questions and equations.\n\nThe power of mathematical abstraction is hard to overstate. The field works with irrational numbers, paradoxes, and possible and impossible worlds, which forces the mind to draw parallels between analogies. The brain basis of math skills is still debated, but it seems centered in the left hemisphere. Dementia, for example, hits the left hemisphere, which can cause logical-mathematical skills to break down. Children with Gerstmann syndrome often have trouble recognizing their fingers and telling left from right.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Spatial intelligence helps you see and move through the world',
        text: 'Picture a large animal like a horse and try to figure out which point is higher, the tip of its tail or the base of its head. As a second test, fold a piece of paper in half three times and try to work out how many rectangular shapes the folds create.\n\nWhen you try these tasks, you will likely know right away whether they come easily. Although the two tests look very different, they both draw on spatial intelligence. They call on mental imagery and a sense of space. Spatial intelligence is the ability to read images accurately, to adjust that image in your mind, and to recreate it even when there is nothing in front of you.\n\nSpatial intelligence shows up in people who can understand and adjust patterns in open spaces and in tight ones. These people can also recognize and handle both large and fine spatial images. Mental imaging, abstract awareness, graphic and creative skills, and active imagination all support spatial intelligence.\n\nMost people think about sight, but spatial intelligence can work even if you cannot see at all. Blind people can have excellent observation skills, even with the loss of sight. People born blind cannot see some features of the world, like color, but they can still judge the size and scale of objects through other senses, like hearing.\n\nEven without sight, spatial ability helps people find their way around and back to where they started. It also sharpens awareness of the small details in art, like paintings or sculptures. It does not matter what the spatial ability is used for. This kind of intelligence shows up in every culture, though some people lean on it more than others. Merging into traffic and picturing the shape of the solar system are two everyday uses of spatial intelligence.\n\nA point worth knowing. Since the brain\'s plasticity drops with age, picking up new languages gets harder the older you get.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Bodily-kinesthetic intelligence shows up in skilled body use',
        text: 'Bodily-kinesthetic intelligence is the use of the whole body, or parts of the body, to solve problems or build things. The process can include using the hands or the mouth.\n\nPeople with bodily-kinesthetic intelligence use their bodies and minds together to pull off skills or solve problems. In many cultures, the way the body moves has little to do with intelligence, since we tend to define intelligence as the ability to think in a logical way. A closer look shows that many thinking tasks have a physical side. A surgeon, for example, has to move with great care to do the work.\n\nYou can train the body to take calculated risks through bodily-kinesthetic intelligence, even when you are not thinking about every move. Famous hockey player Wayne Gretzky would hold the puck for an extra second in front of the net, which threw the goalie off rhythm. That move gave Gretzky time to read the goalie before taking the shot. When he was criticized, he said no one would accuse a doctor of learning the job by instinct, so they should not expect that of him either.\n\nIt is also wrong to say that the brain has no role in physical movement. The brain is involved, but as a tool for the body rather than the goal itself. The central nervous system helps refine, redirect, and adapt motor activity to match a person\'s goals. In short, the body and the brain keep talking to each other to carry out a motor task.\n\nDamage to specific parts of the brain, especially in the left hemisphere, can limit the ability to move and perform motor tasks. The different types of apraxia are an example. A person with apraxia understands what is being asked of them and is physically able and willing to do it, but they cannot actually do it.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Other-people smart and self-smart shape us as people and as a team',
        text: 'Reading other people well means picking up on what drives them, what they want, and what they prefer. Strong readers of others tend to collaborate smoothly. Turning the lens inward, self-smart is about building a working map of who you are and using that map to steer your own choices.\n\nIt is worth being clear about the difference. There are several paths to self-awareness. You have to be able to sit with your own thoughts, feelings, and moods. The French writer Marcel Proust, a novelist, critic, and essayist, is a classic case. His sweeping work In Search of Lost Time is a deep dive into the inner world.\n\nReading other people, on the other hand, is about picking up on their emotional states, personality, possible motives, and intentions. Mahatma Gandhi is a useful example. He had a gift for grasping where people were coming from and guiding them toward a different view.\n\nSmooth communication depends on knowing how to sort your own thoughts and how to speak to others in a way that fits the situation. Both forms of people-smart live in the frontal lobes, where input from the senses mixes with input from the limbic system. Put simply, the frontal lobes are where your reading of other people meets your own emotional data.\n\nEveryone shares the same brain base for these intelligences, but the way they play out in different cultures varies a great deal. The same is true for the other intelligences, which show up in different shapes in different places. Religious traditions, for example, shape the worldview of their followers, so two people from different faiths can look at the same world in very different ways.\n\nSelf-smart and other-people smart quietly shape how we see the world. Society often mirrors who we are, so it pays to know how to read yourself well and how to read the people around you with care.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Final thoughts on multiple intelligences',
        text: 'Studying the many kinds of intelligence goes a long way toward showing how the brain works and how we can tune our neural system to handle things that once looked impossible. The study of the brain is one of the cornerstones of science, and humans have been able to correct some cognitive errors through scientific and psychological research.\n\nDr. Gardner\'s view of intelligence shows that we can have diverse skills in isolation or together. Even though the brain does the heavy lifting of processing information, a fault in one area does not have to drag down the rest. He built the theory of multiple intelligences to show that people are not born with all of their intellect. The theory pushed back on the older idea that general intelligence is only about cognitive ability.\n\nPeople both benefit from and fall victim to changes in their time. A person with one set of skills can be a brilliant mathematician or scientist in one era. Those skills are exactly what that era needs, but they may matter far less in the next, as Dr. Howard Gardner has noted.\n\nGardner\'s model may have grown in popularity because of a simple and attractive idea. Everyone has their own pattern of strengths and weaknesses, and research backs that up. Many people find it more useful to focus on the variety of skills than to assume people only differ in a single number on a test.\n\nA small exercise to try. Set aside time to learn a new skill. Put real effort into getting better at it. Practice often and stay open to feedback.'
      }
    ]
  }
};
